{"topicSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/reduce(_:_:)","doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/flatMap(_:)-33iwm","doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/map(_:)-1vz08"],"anchor":"Topics"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/flatMapError(_:)-7w48m","doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/flatMapError(_:)-kcbe","doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/mapError(_:)"],"title":"Failure != Never","abstract":[{"text":"These compile when Failure == Never, but will generate warnings, and can’t actually do anything there.","type":"text"}],"anchor":"Failure-=-Never"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/flatMap(_:)-8t5th","doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/map(_:)-792vs"],"title":"Failure == Never","abstract":[{"text":"Explicit specializations for more generic overloads.","type":"text"}],"anchor":"Failure-==-Never"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/zip(_:)-50liz","doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/_Concurrency\/Task\/zip(_:)-7kroi"],"title":"Duplicates for `Never` and `any Error`","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"For reasons detailed above, working with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":"s often requires an overload for each of the two supported "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Failure"},{"type":"text","text":" types."}],"anchor":"Duplicates-for-Never-and-any-Error"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"tokens":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"extension"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"typeIdentifier","preciseIdentifier":"s:ScT","text":"Task"}],"platforms":["macOS"],"languages":["swift"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"overview","type":"heading","text":"Overview","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"An asynchronous get-only throwing property wrapper?","type":"text"}]},{"anchor":"","type":"heading","text":"","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Although "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":" qualifies as being a “throwing property wrapper”, and has a lot in common with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Result"},{"type":"text","text":", in particular, it has some key differences to its synchronous cousins."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"First, unlike mutable "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Optional"},{"type":"text","text":"s and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Result"},{"type":"text","text":"s, the value of a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":" exclusively makes sense to be "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"get"},{"type":"text","text":"-only. Although it’s not currently possible in Swift, it might make sense for an asynchronous "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"property","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" to be settable—but not the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"value"},{"type":"text","text":" of a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Other differences show up when taking mapping methods into account:"}]},{"anchor":"flatMap--map","type":"heading","text":"flatMap \/ map","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"With a synchronous wrapper, like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Result"},{"type":"text","text":", mapping can throw a different type of error than the wrapper’s own error type. You can still do that, with "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":". But there’s no way to preserve either of the error types, in the resulting "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":", in doing so."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Mapping methods have to handle the possibility of the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Task","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" failing, or the transformation failing. This requires the transformed ","type":"text"},{"code":"Task","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"’s error type to be ","type":"text"},{"code":"any Error","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"There is an exception:"}],"type":"strong"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"If the original "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":"’s error type is "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Never"},{"type":"text","text":", the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Error"},{"type":"text","text":" type of the transformation could, in theory, match the transformed "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":"’s."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In practice, this is possible, but only when the transformation also ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"doesn’t"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" throw. ","type":"text"},{"code":"Never","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" can be preserved in the transformed ","type":"text"},{"code":"Task","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The reason for this is that, unfortunately, while "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":"s technically can use any type of error, there is no way to create a "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":" whose "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Failure"},{"type":"text","text":" is anything except "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Never"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"any Error"},{"type":"text","text":". Hopefully this limitation will be lifted soon."}]},{"anchor":"flatMapAndMergeError--mapAndMergeError","type":"heading","text":"flatMapAndMergeError \/ mapAndMergeError","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In theory, these would also be exceptions. An error type should be able to be preserved, if only one is used across the transformation."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But for now, “merging error” overloads are not be possible."}]},{"anchor":"mapError","type":"heading","text":"mapError","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In the future, this may be able to provide a true mapping to new ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"text":" type, with a typed ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Failure"},{"text":". For now, it at least can still transform an error—the result just needs to be erased to ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"any Error"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"anchor":"flatMapError","type":"heading","text":"flatMapError","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"There is one special overload of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"flatMapError"},{"type":"text","text":" which allows for a type transformation "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"mapError"},{"type":"text","text":" cannot achieve. If the failure transformation is not throwing, you can return a transformed "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Task"},{"type":"text","text":" whose "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Failure"},{"type":"text","text":" is "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Never"},{"type":"text","text":", instead of "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"any Error"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/thrappture\/_concurrency\/task"]}],"kind":"symbol","seeAlsoSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/Notes-on-Conversion","doc:\/\/Thrappture\/documentation\/Thrappture\/ThrowingPropertyWrapper"],"generated":true}],"sections":[],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"minor":3,"patch":0},"metadata":{"modules":[{"name":"Thrappture",